SQl Tutoral

Database
    -> Database is collection of data in a format that can be easily accessed (Digital).
    -> A Software application used to manage our DB is called DBMS (Database Management System).

Types of Databases
    # Relational DBMS
        -> Data stored in tables.
        Example -> Mysql, Sql Server, Oracle, PostgreSQL.

    # Non-Relation DBMS (NoSQL)
        -> Data not stored is tables.
        Example -> mongoDB

What is SQL?
    -> Structured Query Language.
    -> SQL is a progamming language used to interact with relational databases.
    -> It is used to perform CRUD operations:
        C: Create
        R: Read
        U: Update
        D: Delete

Database Structure

What is Table

Creating our First Database
    -> CREATE DATABASE db_name;  ( create database: can also be used ).
    -> DROP DATABASE db_name; ( drop database:  can also be used ).

Creating our First Table
    -> USE db_name; (use: can also be used ).
    # Creat Table Query
        Syntax
        CREATE TABLE table_name (
            column_name1    datatype    constraint,
            column_name2    datatype    constraint,
            column_name3    datatype    constraint
        );

        Query
        CREATE TABLE student (
            id      INT         PRIMARY KEY,
            name    VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
            age     INT         NOT NULL
        );

SQL Datatypes

        NUMERIC DATA TYPES
    -----------------
    Data Type           Description                                         Usage
    ------------------  --------------------------------------------------  -------------------------
    INT / INTEGER       Stores whole numbers such as 1, 10, -5               INT
    SMALLINT            Stores smaller range whole numbers, saves memory     SMALLINT
    BIGINT              Stores very large whole numbers                      BIGINT
    TINYINT             Stores very small numbers (commonly 0 or 1 in MySQL) TINYINT(1)
    DECIMAL(p,s)        Stores exact decimal values; used for money/salary   DECIMAL(10,2)
    NUMERIC(p,s)        Same as DECIMAL; ensures precision                   NUMERIC(8,2)
    FLOAT               Stores approximate decimal values                    FLOAT
    DOUBLE              Stores larger floating-point numbers                 DOUBLE


    STRING DATA TYPES
    -----------------
    Data Type           Description                                         Usage
    ------------------  --------------------------------------------------  -------------------------
    CHAR(n)             Fixed-length string; unused space is padded          CHAR(5)
    VARCHAR(n)          Variable-length string; saves space                  VARCHAR(100)
    TEXT                Stores large text such as descriptions/comments      TEXT
    LONGTEXT            Stores very large text content (MySQL specific)      LONGTEXT


    DATE & TIME DATA TYPES
    ---------------------
    Data Type           Description                                         Usage
    ------------------  --------------------------------------------------  -------------------------
    DATE                Stores date only in YYYY-MM-DD format                DATE
    TIME                Stores time only in HH:MM:SS format                  TIME
    DATETIME            Stores date and time without timezone                DATETIME
    TIMESTAMP           Stores date and time with timezone support           TIMESTAMP
    YEAR                Stores year value (MySQL specific)                   YEAR


    BOOLEAN DATA TYPE
    -----------------
    Data Type           Description                                         Usage
    ------------------  --------------------------------------------------  -------------------------
    BOOLEAN / BOOL      Stores TRUE or FALSE values (0 or 1 internally)      BOOLEAN


    BINARY DATA TYPES
    -----------------
    Data Type           Description                                         Usage
    ------------------  --------------------------------------------------  -------------------------
    BINARY(n)           Fixed-length binary data                             BINARY(16)
    VARBINARY(n)        Variable-length binary data                          VARBINARY(255)
    BLOB                Stores binary large objects such as images/files     BLOB

    # SQL Datatypes (Signed: For positive and Negative  & Unsigned: For Positive Only)
        
        TINYINT (-128 to 127)
        TINYINT UNSIGNED (0 to 255) ( UNSIGNED: it can increase the range ).

Types of SQL Commands
    # DDL (Data Defination Language): create, alter, rename, truncate & drop
    # DQL (Data Query Language): select
    # DML (Data Manipulation Language): insert, update & delete 
    # DCL (Data Control Language): grant & revoke permission to users
    # TCL (Transaction Control Language): start transaction, commit, rollback

Database related Queries
    -> CREATE DATABASE db_name;
    -> CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS db_name;
    -> DROP DATABASE db_name;
    -> DROP DATABASE IF EXISTS db_name;
    -> SHOW DATABASE;
    -> SHOW TABLES;

Table related Queries
    # Create
        Syntax:
            CREATE TABLE table_name (
                column_name1 datatype constraint;
                column_name2 datatype constraint;
            );

        Sample:
            CREATE TABLE student (
                rollno INT PRIMARY KEY,
                name VARCHAR(50)
            );
    
    # Select & View All columns
        Syntax:
            SELECT * FROM table_name;

        Sample:
            SELECT * FROM student;
    
    # Insert 
        Syntax:
            INSERT INTO table_name (column_name1, column_name2) 
            VALUES 
            (col1_v1, col2_v1), 
            (col1_v2, col2_v2);

        Sample:
            INSERT INTO student (rollno, name)
            VALUES
            (101,"Naseem"),
            (102."Hafiz");

Keys
    # Primary Key
        -> It is a column (or set of columns) in a table that uniquely identites each row. (a unique id)
        -> There is only 1 PK & it should be NOT null.
    
    # Foreign Key
        -> A foreign key is a column (or set of columns) in a table that refers to the primary key of other table.
        -> There can be multiple FK.
        -> FKs can have duplicate & null values. 

Constraints
    -> SQL constraints are used to specify rules for data in a table.
        NOT NULL columns cannot have a null value
        Syntax:     col1 int NOT NULL

        UNIQUE all values in column are diffrent 
        Syntax:     col2 int UNIQUE

        PRIMARY KEY makes a column unique & not null but used only for one
        Syntax:     id int PRIMARY KEY

        Sample:
            CREATE TABLE temp (
                id int not null,
                PRIMARY KEY (id)
            );

        FOREIGN KEY prevent actions that would destroy link between TABLES
        Sample:
            CREATE TABLE temp (
                cust_id int,
                FOREIGN KEY (cust_id) references customer(id)
            );

        DEFAULT sets the default value of a column
            Sample:
                salary INT DEFAULT 25000

        CHECK it can limit the values allowed in a column
            Sample:
                CREATE TABLE city (
                    id INT PRIMARY KEY,
                    city VARCHAR(50),
                    age INT,
                    CONSTRAINT age_check CHECK (age >= 18 AND city = "Delhi")
                );

                CREATE TABLE newTab (
                    age INT CHECK (age >= 18)
                );


